To create a FiveM NUI similar to the one in the image, you can use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Here's an example of how to create the NUI layout using HTML and CSS:

HTML:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
    <title>FiveM NUI</title>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="main">
        <div id="teamA">Team A</div>
        <div id="score">1-1</div>
        <div id="teamB">Team B</div>
    </div>
    <script src="main.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

CSS (styles.css):
```css
body {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
}

#main {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.75);
    padding: 20px;
    margin-top: 20px;
    box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
}

#teamA,
#score,
#teamB {
    margin: 0 20px;
    color: white;
    font-size: 20px;
}

#score {
    font-size: 24px;
    font-weight: bold;
}
```

This code will create a horizontally centered NUI at the top of the page with a layout similar to the one in the image. The score is set as a placeholder (1-1), and you can change it using JavaScript.

For example, you can use JavaScript (main.js) to update the score as follows:

```javascript
// Update the score (example)
function updateScore(newScore) {
    document.getElementById('score').innerText = newScore;
}

// Usage
updateScore('2-3');
```

Just replace the '2-3' with the desired score value, and the function will update the score on the NUI.

